column169: Clean Harbors was dispatched to the site. Upon the contractor’s arrival, personnel observed that the released material impacted a 1ft-by-1ft area and 2ft-by-2ft area of asphalt and a 10ft-by-3ft area of the trailer floor. They estimated that one (1) gallon of material was released most likely due to a forklift puncturing one (1) 55-gallon metal drum. Clean Harbors personnel inspected all 24 drums on the trailer and found only one (1) drum was affected. The damaged 55-gallon metal drum was contained in one (1) 85-gallon metal drum. Contractor personnel deployed granular absorbents to the affected areas and containerized them into one (1) 55-gallon metal drum. The generated waste was staged onsite and will remain onsite for the ESTES DGRM team to coordinate disposal.

On April 4th, 2025, while loading and unloading a shipment of liquid drums at Veolia's 10-day in-transit facility, a Veolia employee picked up a drum of petroleum distillates using the drum gripper to weigh it. During this process, a co-worker noticed a small pinhole leak in the drum. The employees promptly covered the hole with a spill pad and tape to stop the leak, then cleaned up the spilled liquid on the floor using spill dry. The leaking drum was overpacked into a 951H2 container for continued transportation.

column169: XPO-Logistics contacted ERTS regarding a punctured pail containing hazardous product, Vapor Retarder Primer VC. One 55-gallon DM containing impacted oil dry and pallet pieces was generated for waste disposal. XPO will manage all waste created from the incident. No storm-drains, waterways, or soil were involved in this incident.

column169: On 4/3/2025 at approximately 1330 hours, Dangerous Goods Administration received notification of undeclared dangerous goods.  The shipment consisted of 2 fiberboard boxes, each contained multiple bottles of perfume.   AWB# 772715499316 had 22 bottles of perfume and AWB 772787929150 had 19 bottles of perfume.  Customs intercepted the shipment for further investigation, which confirmed the presence of the perfume.  Neither shipment was prepared in accordance with IATA Regulations, as it did not display the required markings, labeling, packaging, or paperwork.  Customs has requested that the shipments be destroyed.

Chris stated that the tank did not appear to be damaged in any way, but there was a noticeable smell comi ng from it. column169: During loading process, EQIS driver discovers drum on pallet with regulated waste material leaking from side, and that generator staff had installed locking ring upside down, and with inadequate ring gasket.  Approximate loss of product from packaging approx. .5 to 1 gallon.  Material cleaned up by staff, cleaning trailer floor and exterior of package.  Our driver re-installed the ring closure appropriately and monitored this package to point of delivery with no further loss of product. Minimal product loss was contained within small area of trailer floor and cleaned up by our staff with no release outside of trailer.
column170: We have assigned our driver to remedial training to help ensure issues like these are identified on the storage room floor and before failing package gets placed on board our vehicle.  We are also liaising with waste generator to ensure their staff understand packaging and closure requirements to inhibit a repeat.  Communication and training.

column169: XPO-Logistics contacted ERTS regarding a punctured leaking poly tote containing hazardous product, Barquat MB-50. A contractor dispatched and observed an estimated 140-gallon release onto the wooden trailer floor, the concrete beneath the trailer, the asphalt parking lot, and the soil. The trailer floor was impacted in a 20’ x 8.5’ area and the concrete beneath the trailer, asphalt, and soil were impacted in a 100’ x 75’ area. The contractor neutralized the release and applied oil dry. A vac truck extracted approximately 2,700-gallons of impacted rainwater and containerized it into one vac box. Three 55-gallon DF’s containing the cut-up tote, impacted oil dry, and impacted PPE were also generated. ERTS will coordinate disposal of the vac box. XPO will manage the drum waste created from the response. No storm-drains or waterways were involved in this incident.

On 4/3/2025 at approximately 1230 hours, Dangerous Goods Administration received notification of undeclared dangerous goods.  The shipment consisted of 50 bottles:  5@70ml, 3@75ml, 32@100ml, 3@125ml, 4@120ml, & 3@80ml. Customs intercepted the shipment for further investigation, which confirmed suspicions of undeclared dangerous goods.  The shipment was not prepared in accordance with IATA Regulations, missing the required markings, labeling, packaging, and paperwork.  The shipment was refused at entry and Customs has requested disposal.

column169: XPO-Logistics contacted ERTS regarding a leaking 55-gallon metal drum containing hazardous product, Leaded Race Fuel. A contractor dispatched and observed an estimated 55-gallons released onto the entire wooden trailer floor, the asphalt beneath the trailer in a 60’x10’ area, and a drain (catch basin) as a result of a forklift puncture. The contractor cleaned up the release using a vac truck and oil dry. One 85-gallon DF containing the empty damaged drum was generated for waste disposal along with three 55-gallon DM’s containing impacted absorbents, and 2,800-gallons of impacted water inside of the vac truck. XPO will manage the waste drums created from the response and ERTS will coordinate disposal of the vac truck liquids at a local third-party disposal site. No waterways or soil were involved in this incident.
